TY  - JOUR
T1  - Managing Legitimacy: Strategic and Institutional Approaches
AU  - Suchman, Mark C.
Y1  - 1995/07/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1995.9508080331
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1995.9508080331
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 571
EP  - 610
VL  - 20
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article synthesizes the large but diverse literature on organizational legitimacy, highlighting similarities and disparities among the leading strategic and institutional approaches. The analysis identifies three primary forms of legitimacy: pragmatic, based on audience self-interest; moral, based on normative approval: and cognitive, based on comprehensibility and taken-for-grantedness. The article then examines strategies for gaining, maintaining, and repairing legitimacy of each type, suggesting both the promises and the pitfalls of such instrumental manipulations.
AB  - This article synthesizes the large but diverse literature on organizational legitimacy, highlighting similarities and disparities among the leading strategic and institutional approaches. The analysis identifies three primary forms of legitimacy: pragmatic, based on audience self-interest; moral, based on normative approval: and cognitive, based on comprehensibility and taken-for-grantedness. The article then examines strategies for gaining, maintaining, and repairing legitimacy of each type, suggesting both the promises and the pitfalls of such instrumental manipulations.
